---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import HorizontalCard from "../components/HorizontalCard.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="Research Projects" sideBarActiveItemID="projects">
  <div>
    <div class="text-3xl w-full font-bold mb-5">Research Projects</div>
    <div class="text-lg mb-8 text-base-content/70">
      Most of my work starts with a deceptively simple question - why, how many, how much, or where exactly?
      Answering it usually requires building something new: a pipeline, a model, a framework.
      Here are some of the problems I've enjoyed solving.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="text-2xl w-full font-bold mb-2">Neuroscience &amp; Brain Imaging</div>

  <HorizontalCard
    title="Brainwide Microglia & Plaque Quantification for Prime-Edited Sleep Restoration in Alzheimer's"
    img="/sleepbrains.jpg"
    desc="Quantification of plaques and microglia in whole murine brains for a study on prime editing of the β1 adrenoceptor to restore physiological REM sleep in an Alzheimer's disease mouse model. Machine learning-based instance segmentation (ilastik) combined with deformable registration to the Allen Brain Atlas for region-specific analysis of pathological markers."
    url="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-025-65964-w"
    badge="Nature Communications 2025"
    tags={['3D image analysis', 'Alzheimer\'s disease', 'ilastik', 'Machine Learning']}
  />
  <div class="divider my-0"></div>

  <HorizontalCard
    title="Drug Efficacy of Netoglitazone in Alzheimer's via Brainwide Microglia Segmentation & Mapping"
    img="/Microglia_hr.jpg"
    desc="Quantification of brainwide, region-specific effects of the antidiabetic drug netoglitazone in Alzheimer's mouse models, using quantitative whole-brain 3D histochemistry (Q3D) and light-sheet microscopy. Whole-brain 3D stacks processed with a custom pipeline for automated microglia segmentation, registration to the Allen Brain Atlas, and statistical mapping."
    url="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0309489"
    badge="PLoS One 2025"
    tags={['3D image analysis', 'Drug efficacy', 'Machine Learning', 'Neurodegeneration']}
  />
  <div class="divider my-0"></div>

  <HorizontalCard
    title="Intracellular Protein Delivery to Neurons via Engineered Toxoplasma: 3D Brainwide Analysis"
    img="/avg_all_groups_hr.jpg"
    desc="An international collaboration developing a novel protein-based delivery system to the central nervous system using engineered Toxoplasma gondii secretion systems. 3D images of whole mouse-brain scans were used to quantify and map the brainwide spatial distribution of the delivered proteins, using light-sheet microscopy (mesoSPIM). Image processing was performed using a custom, in-house developed pipeline employing shared-memory parallelism, targeted for fast processing of large 3D image datasets."
    url="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41564-024-01750-6"
    badge="Nature Microbiology 2024"
    tags={['3D segmentation', 'HPC', 'Light-sheet microscopy', 'Machine Learning']}
  />
  <div class="divider my-0"></div>

  <div class="text-2xl w-full font-bold mb-2 mt-10">Computational Biophysics</div>

  <HorizontalCard
    title="Inertial Focusing of Spherical Particles in Microfluidic Channels"
    img="/inertial_focusing.png"
    desc="Does particle rotation matter in microfluidic cell sorting? Large-scale simulations reveal that freely rotating particles focus at drastically different positions than non-rotating ones — overturning the assumption that rotation-induced lift is negligible. A new phenomenological model captures this effect, opening the door to improved designs for inertia-based microfluidic devices."
    url="https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevFluids.10.054202"
    badge="Phys. Rev. Fluids 2025"
    tags={['Dissipative particle dynamics', 'Inertial focusing', 'Microfluidics']}
  />
  <div class="divider my-0"></div>

  <HorizontalCard
    title="Optimal Red Blood Cell Volume for Oxygen Transport in Arterioles"
    img="/optimal_rbc_shape.png"
    desc="Is the volume of a red blood cell optimized by nature? High-fidelity simulations reveal that RBCs with healthy volumes maximize the cell-free layer thickness in arterioles — the region of greatest flow resistance — making them optimally efficient for oxygen transport. Too small and they deform and fold; too large and they collide into diffuse trajectories. Nature, it turns out, got the volume just right."
    url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.bpj.2024.04.015"
    badge="Biophysical Journal 2024"
    tags={['Microfluidics', 'Oxygen transport', 'Red blood cells']}
  />
  <div class="divider my-0"></div>

  <HorizontalCard
    title="Stress-Free State & Viscoelastic Properties of Red Blood Cells"
    img="/rbc-sfs_hr.jpg"
    desc="Can three simple experiments capture everything about a red blood cell? We show that resting shape, optical tweezers stretching, and relaxation dynamics are sufficient to infer all viscoelastic properties and the stress-free state via hierarchical Bayesian inference — yielding a transferable model that predicts cell dynamics in unseen shear flow conditions with unprecedented accuracy."
    url="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0006349523001728"
    badge="Biophysical Journal 2023"
    tags={['Bayesian inference', 'Hierarchical models', 'Membrane mechanics']}
  />
  <div class="divider my-0"></div>

  <HorizontalCard
    title="Hierarchical Bayesian UQ for Red Blood Cell Models"
    img="/hb-rbc.png"
    desc="Hierarchical Bayesian inference for calibrating a red blood cell model using data from optical tweezers stretching and tank treading in shear flows. Demonstrated that hierarchical models outperform single-level Bayesian calibration at predicting unseen data, advancing the development of robust, transferable RBC models."
    url="https://journals.aps.org/prapplied/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevApplied.15.034062"
    badge="Phys. Rev. Applied 2021"
    tags={['Bayesian inference', 'Hierarchical models', 'Membrane mechanics']}
  />
  <div class="divider my-0"></div>

  <div class="text-2xl w-full font-bold mb-2 mt-10">HPC &amp; Frameworks</div>

  <HorizontalCard
    title="Korali — Large-Scale Bayesian UQ Framework"
    img="/korali_hr.jpg"
    desc="An open-source framework for large-scale Bayesian uncertainty quantification and stochastic optimization. The framework relies on non-intrusive sampling of complex multiphysics models with a distributed sampling engine featuring novel fault tolerance and load balancing for massively-parallel architectures."
    url="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0045782521005752"
    badge="CMAME 2022"
    tags={['Bayesian inference', 'HPC', 'Open-source', 'Stochastic optimization']}
  />
  <div class="divider my-0"></div>

  <HorizontalCard
    title="Load Balancing in Large Scale Bayesian Inference"
    img="/loadbalancing_uq-rbc.png"
    desc="A novel strategy for load balancing in large-scale Bayesian inference, addressing workload imbalance in population-based sampling methods by concurrently scheduling independent experiments on shared worker nodes. Demonstrated on 512 nodes of the Piz Daint supercomputer for data-driven calibration of red blood cell membrane viscosity using hierarchical Bayesian inference."
    url="https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1145/3394277.3401849"
    badge="PASC 2020"
    tags={['Bayesian inference', 'Distributed computing', 'Load balancing']}
  />
</BaseLayout>
